M||tx|---
M||titl|Early Length Check for Array Comparisons
M||impa|md-hi
M||impa|avoids expensive operations when lengths differ
M||tags|javascript, arrays, perf, op, comparison
M||tx|---
M|Earl|tx|When comparing arrays w/ expensive operations (sorting, deep equality, serialization), check lengths first. If lengths differ, the arrays cannot be equal.
M|Earl|tx|In real-world applications, this op is esp valuable when the comparison runs in hot paths (event handlers, render loops).
M|Earl|**In|**
M|Earl|tx|```ts
M|Earl|func|string[], original: string[]) {
M|Earl|tx|// Always sorts and joins, even when lengths differ
M|Earl|tx|return current.sort().join() !== original.sort().join()
M|Earl|tx|}
M|Earl|tx|```
M|Earl|tx|Two O(n log n) sorts run even when `current.length` is 5 and `original.length` is 100. There is also overhead of joining the arrays and comparing the strings.
M|Earl|**Co|**
M|Earl|tx|```ts
M|Earl|func|string[], original: string[]) {
M|Earl|tx|// Early return if lengths differ
M|Earl|tx|if (current.length !== original.length) {
M|Earl|tx|return true
M|Earl|tx|}
M|Earl|tx|// Only sort when lengths match
M|Earl|tx|const currentSorted = current.toSorted()
M|Earl|tx|const originalSorted = original.toSorted()
M|Earl|tx|for (let i = 0; i < currentSorted.length; i++) {
M|Earl|tx|if (currentSorted[i] !== originalSorted[i]) {
M|Earl|tx|return true
M|Earl|tx|}
M|Earl|tx|}
M|Earl|tx|return false
M|Earl|tx|}
M|Earl|tx|```
M|Earl|This|
M|Earl|it|It avoids the overhead of sorting and joining the arrays when lengths differ
M|Earl|it|It avoids consuming memory for the joined strings (esp important for large arrays)
M|Earl|it|It avoids mutating the original arrays
M|Earl|it|It returns early when a difference is found